Package net.tp.utils.classes

Class LocalMonthDayTime

java.lang.Object
net.tp.utils.classes.LocalMonthDayTime
public class LocalMonthDayTime extends Object
A date-time without a time-zone and without year in the ISO-8601 calendar system, such as --12-03T10:15:30.

LocalMonthDayTime is a date-time object without year that represents a date-time without year, often viewed as --month-day-hour-minute-second. Other date and time fields, such as day-of-year, day-of-week and week-of-year, can also be accessed. Time is represented to nanosecond precision. For example, the value "3rd September at 10:15:30" can be stored in a LocalMonthDayTime.

This class does not store or represent a time-zone. Instead, it is a description of the date without year, combined with the local time as seen on a wall clock. It cannot represent an instant on the time-line without additional information such as an offset or time-zone.

Since:
1.0.0

    • from

      public static LocalMonthDayTime from(TemporalAccessor temporalAccessor)
      Obtains an instance of LocalMonthDayTime from a temporal object.

      This obtains a local date-time without year based on the specified temporal. A TemporalAccessor represents an arbitrary set of date and time information, which factory converts to an instance of LocalMonthDayTime.

      The conversion extracts and combines the LocalDate and the LocalTime from the temporal object. Implementations are permitted to perform optimizations such as accessing those fields that are equivalent to the relevant objects.

      This method matches the signature of the functional interface TemporalQuery allowing it to be used as a query via method reference, LocalMonthDayTime::from.

      Parameters:
      temporalAccessor - the temporal object to convert; if null current
      Returns:
      the local date-time; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if unable to convert to a MonthDay or LocalTime
      Since:
      1.0.0

    • isAfter

      public boolean isAfter(LocalMonthDayTime other, boolean firstLeap, boolean secondLeap)
      Checks if date-time without year is after the specified date-time without year.

      This checks to see if date-time without year represents a point on the local time-line after the other date-time without year. 

         LocalMonthDayTime a = LocalMonthDayTime.of(6, 30, 12, 00);
   LocalMonthDayTime b = LocalMonthDayTime.of(7, 1, 12, 00);
   a.isAfter(b) == false
   a.isAfter(a) == false
   b.isAfter(a) == true

      This method only considers the position of the two date-times without years on the local time-line. It does not take into account the chronology, or calendar system.

      Parameters:
      other - the other date-time without year to compare to; if null current
      firstLeap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      secondLeap - true if the parameter year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      true if date-time without year is after the specified date-time
      Since:
      1.0.0

    • minus

      public LocalMonthDayTime minus(long amountToSubtract, ChronoUnit unit, boolean leap)
      Returns a copy of date-time with the specified amount subtracted.

      This returns a LocalMonthDayTime, based on one, with the amount in terms of the unit subtracted. If it is not possible to subtract the amount, because the unit is not supported or for some other reason, an exception is thrown.

      This method is equivalent to plus(long, ChronoUnit, boolean) with the amount negated. See that method for a full description of how addition, and thus subtraction, works.

      Parameters:
      amountToSubtract - the amount of the unit to subtract from the result, may be negative
      unit - the unit of the amount to subtract; not null
      leap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      a LocalDateTimeWithoutException based on date-time with the specified amount subtracted; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the subtraction cannot be made
      UnsupportedTemporalTypeException - if the unit is not supported
      ArithmeticException - if numeric overflow occurs
      Since:
      1.0.0

      public static LocalMonthDayTime of(int month, int day, int hour, int min, int sec, int nanoOfSec)
      Obtains an instance of LocalMonthDayTime from month, day, hour, minute, second and nanosecond.

      This returns a LocalMonthDayTime with the specified month, day-of-month, hour, minute, second and nanosecond. The day must be valid for the year and month, otherwise an exception will be thrown.

      hour - the hour-of-day to represent, from 0 to 23
      min - the minute-of-hour to represent, from 0 to 59
      sec - the second-of-minute to represent, from 0 to 59
      nanoOfSec - the nano-of-second to represent, from 0 to 999,999,999
      Returns:

      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the value of any field is out of range or invalid

      1.0.0

    • plusDays

      public LocalMonthDayTime plusDays(long amountToAdd, boolean leap)
      Returns a copy of LocalMonthDayTime with the specified number of years added.

      This method adds the specified amount to the years field in three steps:

      1. Add the input years to the year field
      2. Check if the resulting date would be invalid
      3. Adjust the day-of-month to the last valid day if necessary
      Parameters:
      amountToAdd - the years to add, may be negative
      leap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      a LocalMonthDayTime based on date-time without year with the years added; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the result exceeds the supported date range
      Since:
      1.0.0

    • plusWeeks

      public LocalMonthDayTime plusWeeks(long amountToAdd, boolean leap)
      Returns a copy of LocalMonthDayTime with the specified number of weeks added.

      This method adds the specified amount in weeks to the days field incrementing the month and year fields as necessary to ensure the result remains valid. The result is only invalid if the maximum/minimum year is exceeded.

      For example, --12-31 plus one week would result in --01-07.

      Parameters:
      amountToAdd - the weeks to add, may be negative
      leap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      a LocalMonthDayTime based on date-time without year with the weeks added; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the result exceeds the supported date range
      Since:
      1.0.0

    • plus

      public LocalMonthDayTime plus(LocalMonthDayTime other, boolean firstLeap, boolean secondLeap)
      Returns an instance of LocalMonthDayTime that is the sum of the LocalMonthDayTime that you are considering and the one that you passed like a parameter.
      Parameters:
      other - the date-time without year that you want to sum to the reference one; if null current
      firstLeap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      secondLeap - true if the parameter year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      a LocalDateTimeWithoutException based on date-time with the specified amount subtracted; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the subtraction cannot be made
      ArithmeticException - if numeric overflow occurs
      Since:
      1.0.0

    • plus

      public LocalMonthDayTime plus(long amountToAdd, ChronoUnit unit, boolean leap)
      Returns a copy of date-time without year with the specified amount added.

      This returns a LocalMonthDayTime, based on one, with the amount in terms of the unit added. If it is not possible to add the amount, because the unit is not supported or for some other reason, an exception is thrown.

      Date units are added as per LocalDate.plus(long, TemporalUnit). Time units are added as per LocalTime.plus(long, TemporalUnit) with any overflow in days added equivalent to using plusDays(long, boolean)}.

      Parameters:
      amountToAdd - the amount of the unit to add to the result, may be negative
      unit - the unit of the amount to add; not null
      leap - true if the year is a leap year and 29 days will be calculated for the month of February for the reference year
      Returns:
      a LocalDateTime based on date-time with the specified amount added; not null
      Throws:
      DateTimeException - if the addition cannot be made
      UnsupportedTemporalTypeException - if the unit is not supported
      ArithmeticException - if numeric overflow occurs
      Since:
      1.0.0
